 I have to display a list of rows on UI. I have millions of rows. How can i do that in a performant way?

 This is another classic system design and frontend architecture question. The fundamental rule here is: You cannot, and should not, load millions of rows into the browser. Even if the network could handle it, the browser's DOM (Document Object Model) would crash trying to render that many HTML elements.

To answer this in an interview, you need to attack the problem from two sides: Frontend Rendering and Backend Data Fetching.

Here is how you break it down for the interviewer.

1. The Frontend Strategy: UI Virtualization (Windowing)

Even if you only fetch 1,000 rows, rendering 1,000 DOM elements at once can cause the UI to stutter. The solution for the frontend is UI Virtualization (also known as Windowing).

How it works: Instead of rendering all the rows in the HTML, a virtualized grid only renders the rows that are currently visible in the user's viewport, plus a small buffer of rows just above and below it.

The Magic: As the user scrolls down, the grid doesn't create new HTML elements. Instead, it recycles the DOM elements that just scrolled off the top of the screen, moves them to the bottom, and updates their data.

Libraries: Mention that you wouldn't build this from scratch unless required. You would use industry-standard libraries like ag-Grid, react-window, or react-virtualized.

2. The Backend Strategy: Data Fetching
Since you cannot send millions of rows to the frontend, the backend must feed the data in small chunks (e.g., 50 or 100 rows at a time) as the user scrolls. You have two main ways to implement this in the database:

Approach A: Offset-based Pagination (The Rookie Way)
This is what most people learn first. You pass a page number and a page size to the backend, and the database runs a query like: SELECT * FROM table LIMIT 50 OFFSET 100000;

Why it fails at scale: Offset pagination is terrible for millions of rows. To skip 100,000 rows, the database literally has to scan 100,000 rows, throw them away, and return the next 50. As the user scrolls deeper, the queries get progressively slower.

Approach B: Cursor-based Pagination (The Senior Way)
Also known as Keyset Pagination. Instead of saying "skip 100,000 rows", the frontend passes a "cursor"—usually the ID or timestamp of the last item it saw. The database query looks like: SELECT * FROM table WHERE id > last_seen_id LIMIT 50;

Why it wins at scale: If the id column is indexed, the database jumps directly to that specific ID in the index and grabs the next 50 rows instantly. It takes the exact same amount of time to fetch page 1 as it does to fetch page 10,000.




Or I can impose a policy that deletes data older than 30 days?

In the industry, this is known as implementing a Data Retention Policy or setting a TTL (Time to Live) on your records. It is one of the most effective ways to keep a system performant, and it completely sidesteps the need for complex pagination or UI virtualization.

Here is a breakdown of why this is a great idea, along with the reality checks you need to consider before proposing it.

Why It's a Great Approach
Guaranteed Performance: If the database only ever holds 30 days of data, your tables stay incredibly lean. Indexes fit perfectly into RAM, and queries return instantly.

Cost Reduction: You drastically reduce your cloud database storage costs by continuously pruning old records.

Privacy and Compliance: If you are dealing with user behavior or personal data, deleting it automatically after 30 days makes compliance with privacy laws (like GDPR or CCPA) significantly easier.

The Reality Checks (What to Watch Out For)
Before you run a DELETE script, you have to verify that the business can legally and operationally survive without that data.

Legal and Regulatory Requirements: If this is financial data, invoices, or healthcare records, the law often mandates that you keep it for 3 to 7 years. A 30-day delete policy would be illegal in those contexts.

Business Intelligence (BI): The marketing or sales teams might rely on that historical data to run year-over-year comparisons or train machine learning models.

The "Best of Both Worlds" Alternative: Archiving
If the business pushes back and says, "We can't delete it, we might need it someday!", you don't have to give up. The industry-standard compromise is Data Tiering / Archiving.

Instead of a hard deletion, you build a background cron job that runs every night:

It takes data older than 30 days from your Hot Database (your fast, expensive SQL database).

It moves those rows into a Data Warehouse or Cold Storage (like AWS S3, Snowflake, or Google BigQuery), which is incredibly cheap to store.

It deletes the rows from the Hot Database.

The UI stays lightning fast because it only queries the hot database, but the data analysts can still run their massive reports against the cold storage.